{{Politics of Mauritania}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Mauritania]] on June 25, 2006 and approved by nearly 97% of voters. Following the August 2005 ouster of long-time president [[Maaouya Ould Sid'Ahmed Taya]], the new transitional military regime called the [[referendum]] on a new [[constitution]], which limits presidents to two five-year terms; previously presidential terms were six years and there was no limit on re-election.<ref>[http://www.middle-east-online.com/English/mauritania/?id=16850 "Mauritania's constitution gets 96.96% yes vote"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020021055/http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/mauritania/?id=16850 |date=2006-10-20 }}, Middle East Online, June 28, 2006.</ref> The new constitution also establishes a maximum age limit of 75 for presidential candidates.<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=54145&SelectRegion=West_Africa&SelectCountry=MAURITANIA "Military junta launches pro-democracy poll"], IRIN, June 23, 2006.</ref>
